            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Kim\u2019s story is etched into the fog-laced avenues of San Francisco\u2019s western neighborhoods. The only son of Korean immigrants who ran a small grocery store in the Richmond District, David\u2019s upbringing was defined by the quiet hum of diligence and the tangible weight of sacrifice. He watched his parents work tirelessly, their hopes for him pinned not on wealth, but on the stability of a respectable profession. This steered him towards the practical world of engineering. He attended San Jose State University, drawn to the logic and order of mechanical design, a stark contrast to the city\u2019s chaotic energy.\n\nHis career began in the late 1990s, a steady climb through the ranks of Silicon Valley hardware companies. While others chased fleeting startup glory, David found his niche in manufacturing\u2014the unglamorous but essential process of turning brilliant designs into physical products. The dot-com bust was a pivotal moment; he saw brilliant colleagues lose everything overnight. The experience hardened his belief in tangible results over hype, cementing his reputation as a reliable, no-nonsense leader. This ethos guided him to his current role as a Director of Hardware Manufacturing, where he is the essential linchpin ensuring that complex electronics are built, tested, and shipped on schedule.\n\nDavid met his wife, Sarah, an urban planner for a small municipality, in their late twenties. They bought a modest home in the Sunset District, a neighborhood whose deliberate pace matched their own, and raised two children there. Those children are now in college, leaving the house feeling both larger and quieter.\n\nHis daily routine is a well-worn groove: the 11.5-mile drive from the Sunset down to his office in South San Francisco is his time for news podcasts and mental preparation. Evenings are for dinners with Sarah and calls with the kids. While he appreciates the city\u2019s beauty\u2014weekend walks in Golden Gate Park, the occasional dinner in North Beach\u2014he feels a generational disconnect from its modern, tech-centric vibrancy.\n\nAt 54, David's ambitions have shifted inward. He no longer dreams of a C-suite position. Instead, he aspires to a quieter future: mentoring young engineers, perhaps consulting part-time, and finally having the time to indulge his passion project\u2014restoring a vintage sports car in his garage, a return to the pure, hands-on engineering that first captured his imagination."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being ten years old, tasked with stacking cans of Sunkist into a perfect pyramid in his parents\u2019 Richmond market. His father adjusted one can, not for aesthetics, but for stability. \u201cAlways build a strong base, David-ah,\u201d he\u2019d said. In that moment, the endless work wasn't just a chore; it was the physical foundation they were painstakingly laying for him. The lesson was about more than soda cans. It was the blueprint for a life built on reliability, not flash.\n\n2.\nIt was 2001. David watched Mark, an engineer who\u2019d boasted about his stock options a month prior, quietly packing his Aeron chair into a cardboard box. The whiteboard behind him was still covered in vaporware architecture. David felt not triumph, but a cold affirmation. He saw the stark difference between a brilliant idea and a product you can hold in your hand. That day, his career path was set: he would make things that were real, tangible, and necessary.\n\n3.\nOn their third date, walking along the Great Highway, Sarah gestured towards the Sunset\u2019s rigid grid. \u201cMost people find it boring,\u201d she said, \u201cbut I love its logic. An orderly response to the chaos of the coast.\u201d David, used to seeing the city as just a series of commutes, felt a profound sense of recognition. He wasn't just falling for her; he was falling for a shared way of seeing the world\u2014finding a quiet beauty in the underlying design of things.\n\n4.\nTwo years ago, after dropping their son at the airport for his freshman year, he and Sarah returned to the empty house. He stood in the hallway, the silence no longer peaceful but vast and unfamiliar. The faint scuff marks on the wall, once a daily annoyance, were now artifacts of a finished project. It wasn't sadness, exactly, but the quiet click of a phase change. The space once filled with family logistics was now his own to redefine.\n\n5.\nLast year, after a brutal quarterly review call filled with supply-chain jargon, he escaped to the garage. He ran a hand over the dusty fender of the '68 Triumph TR6. He smelled the faint scent of oil and old leather, a world away from spreadsheets and PowerPoints. In the cold, solid feel of the steel, he reconnected with his beginning: the pure, mechanical logic of an engine. This wasn't just a car; it was his next design problem, and the first in years that felt entirely his."
